    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-05-18T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-05-18T01:00:00-05:00" n="365"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d365">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/6287: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Tientsin (<persName type="from"
                            >Lockhart</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tientsin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-05-18T14:00:00+08:00"
                            >May 18, 1933—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 18—4:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The explosion of a bomb on a railway bridge near Tientsin central station
                    yesterday just before the arrival of Huang Fu’s special train is interpreted as
                    an attempt on the life of Huang and resulted in the arrest and execution of a
                    slightly wounded Chinese caught near the bridge shortly after the explosion. The
                    Chinese is said to have confessed receiving money for placing the bomb on the
                    bridge. Bombings are of almost daily occurrence here now.</p>
                <pb facs="0435" n="333" xml:id="pg_333"/>
                <p>There has apparently been little actual fighting in the Lwanchow region and
                    progress west of that place has been slow. Considerable looting by retreating
                    forces has occurred. The damage to the Lwanchow bridge previously reported will
                    require about 3 weeks to repair, according to American military report.</p>
                <p>The Tientsin Bureau of Public Safety has been put under the direct control of the
                    Provincial Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
